{{Infobox NRHP | name = Underwriters Salvage Corps | nrhp_type = | image = Underwriters Salvage Corps in Cincinnati.jpg | caption = Front of the Salvage Corps | location= 110-112 E. 8th St., [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|6|18|N|84|30|42|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Ohio#USA | built = 1897 | architect = William Schuberth | architecture = [[Queen Anne Style architecture (United States)|Queen Anne]] | added = July 15, 1982 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 82003589<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }}
The '''Underwriters Salvage Corps''' is a historic building in [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. Located on Eighth Street in the city's [[downtown Cincinnati|downtown]], it has historically been the home of a firm that worked together with both the [[Cincinnati Fire Department]] and local [[Property insurance|fire insurance]] companies.<ref name=dohp>Owen, Lorrie K., ed. ''Dictionary of Ohio Historic Places''. Vol. 1. [[St. Clair Shores, Michigan|St. Clair Shores]]: Somerset, 1999, 681-682.</ref>
Local insurance companies formed the Underwriters Salvage Corps in 1886 at the end of a four-year-long process of negotiations. As a [[Salvage Corps|salvage corps]], their goal was largely to assist firefighters in danger zones: employees rushed to burning buildings to try to save both lives and property, and they were accorded the same status as official firefighters while at fire zones.<ref name=dohp />
The present building was erected in 1897 under the direction of local contractor William Schuberth; its purpose was the storage of equipment and the housing of the Salvage Corps' employees who were on duty at any given point.<ref name=dohp /> A brick building with a stone [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]],<ref name=ohs>{{OHC NRHP|82003589|Underwriters Salvage Corps}}, [[Ohio Historical Society]], 2007. Accessed 2010-11-02.</ref> it is a [[Queen Anne Style architecture (United States)|Queen Anne]] structure three-and-a-half [[storey|stories]] tall.<ref name=dohp />
In 1982, the Underwriters Salvage Corps was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=nris /> Key to this designation was its place in local history,<ref name=ohs /> for it was the only Cincinnati-area corporation that worked closely with both insurance companies and the city's fire department.<ref name=dohp />
